Tutorial: Analysis of Top Streamers on Twitch¶

Introduction¶

In the past few years, people have reduced the frequency of outdoor activities due to the spread of the epidemic. This phenomenon has given rise to the rapid growth of the live-streaming industry, with many people choosing to spend time watching live streams at home during the epidemic.

In this tutorial, we'll analyze the top 1000 Twitch streamer in 2021. This data is available on kaggle. According to the instructions, the data will be updated once a year, but the 2022 version has not been updated yet, so we will start with the 2021 data.

We will go over loading data, organizing data, analyzing data. We can also formulate some hypotheses from the data and prove them by statistical methods. We hope our analysis can provide some insights for other people who want to become Streamers.

Data¶

The library we are going to use is pandas, pandas is a package allow us to manipulate large dataset like excel Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/aayushmishra1512/twitchdata To make things easier, here's a mirror to this dataset: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/liujiahua123123/320Final/main/twitchdata-update.csv

Explanation of this dataset:

  • Channel: The name of this streamer
  • Watch time: Total time this streamer was watched
  • Stream time: Total time this streamer streaming
  • Peak viewers: The highest viewer at the same time this year
  • Average viewers: The average time this streamer was watched
  • Followers: number of followers
  • Followers gained: number of followers gained this year
  • Views gained: number of views gained this year
  • Partnered: is this streamer works for Twitch.tv
  • Mature: is this streamer age > 18
  • Language: what language does this streamer speak

At this stage, we want to add some new columns, that would benefit our following analysis. Pinpointing to the fact that The earlier Streamer starts live-streaming, the more likely it is to accumulate more followers.

It is not fair to compare the number of followers across streamer, we should rather compare the percentage of growth in followers. We can use the following formula to do this

Growth = Followers Gained / ( Followers - Followers Gained )

Growth would be a float number, indicate the growth of followers for each streamer in terms of rate.

In [38]:
# This is a batch operation, more like vector operation, it produced the exactly same result as you would do it element by element. But this approach is more efficiency
data['Growth'] = data['Followers gained'] / (data['Followers'] - data['Followers gained'])
data['Growth'].describe()

Data exploration and analysis is defined as the process of examining a dataset in order to gain insights and better understand its characteristics. This typically involves using various techniques and tools to explore the data, such as visualizing the data using graphs and charts, summarizing the data using descriptive statistics, and looking for patterns and trends in the data. The goal of data exploration and analysis is to discover useful information that can help inform decision-making and guide further research or investigation.

# Define a function to map language values to colors
def language_to_color(l):
    if l == 'English':
        return "orangered"
    return "skyblue"

# Make a copy of the data to avoid modifying the original data
data_copied_0 = data.copy()

# Add a new column 'isEnglish' that is True if the 'Language' column is 'English' and False otherwise
data_copied_0['isEnglish'] = data_copied_0['Language'] == 'English'

# Get the maximum value in the 'Watch time(Minutes)' column to use as the x-axis limit
x_max = max(data['Watch time(Minutes)'])

# Set up figure and axes for scatter plot
fig5, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(12, 8))

# Create scatter plot with 'Watch time(Minutes)' on x-axis and 'Views gained' on y-axis,
# and color each point based on the 'Language' column
ax.scatter(x=data_copied_0['Watch time(Minutes)'], y=data_copied_0['Views gained'],
           c=data_copied_0['Language'].apply(language_to_color))

# Set labels and title for the plot
ax.set_xlabel('Watch time (Minutes)')
ax.set_ylabel('Views gained')
ax.set_title('Views gained V.S Watch time', loc='center')

# Create legend for the scatter plot
import matplotlib.lines as mlines
english_mark = mlines.Line2D([], [], color='orangered', marker='o', linestyle='None',
                             markersize=7, label='English')
non_english_mark = mlines.Line2D([], [], color='skyblue', marker='o', linestyle='None',
                                 markersize=7, label='Non-English')
ax.legend(handles=[english_mark, non_english_mark])


from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
# create regression line for each group, we group it by if that's english
for c, dl in data_copied_0.groupby(['isEnglish']):
    import numpy as np
    # reshape,
    # we need to have array of feature array.
    X = np.array(dl['Watch time(Minutes)']).reshape(-1, 1)
    Y = dl['Views gained']
    # create regression line
    reg = LinearRegression().fit(X, Y)
    # pretty print the model
    sign = "+" if reg.intercept_ > 0 else "-"
    ax.add_line(mlines.Line2D(alpha=0.5, ls='--', xdata=[0, x_max], ydata=[reg.predict([[0]]), reg.predict([[x_max]])],
                              c="orangered" if c else "skyblue"))

In a linear regression model, the dependent variable is predicted from the independent variable using a linear equation. This equation takes the form Y = a + bX, where X is the independent variable, Y is the dependent variable, 'a' is the intercept, and 'b' is the slope of the line. Linear regression is used to analyze the relationship between two variables and to make predictions about the dependent variable based on the value of the independent variable.

As can be seen from the figure, the slopes of the two regression lines are not the same. Means they have different 'b'. This suggests that language speaking plays a role in affecting views gained. For the same amount of watch time, streamer who speak non-english get a higher views than those speak english. Frankly speaking, this is counter-intuitive, because people who watch Twitter mainly speaks English.

Next, we use similar approach to check if Mature and Partner plays a role in this relationship.

We next prove in a more mathematical way that these relations hold.

Hypothesis testing¶

Hypothesis testing is a statistical method used to determine whether there is sufficient evidence in a sample of data to infer a certain property of a population.

Hypothesis testing is done by defining a null hypothesis, which represents the default assumption that there is no relationship between the variables being studied, and an alternative hypothesis, which represents the claim that there is a relationship between the variables.

Normally, null hypothesis represent the hypothesis that nothing happens. For example, there's no relationship between views gained and watch time. Alternative hypothesis represent the hypothesis that we wish to prove exists. We can not say we 'accept' the alternative hypothesis, but say we 'reject' the null hypothesis.

More about Hypothesis Testing

The package we will be using is statmodel.

The statsmodels package is a python module that provides classes and functions for the estimation of many different statistical models, as well as for conducting statistical tests, and statistical data exploration.

The first hypothesis test we will do is linear regression analysis. This type of test involves fitting a linear regression model to the data and evaluating its statistical significance. Our null hypothesis is that views and watch time has no relation. The alternative hypothesis is that there's a linear relationship between views and watch time.

In [40]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

# Make a copy of the data and rename the columns for use with statsmodels
data_copied_for_smf = data.copy()
data_copied_for_smf['Y'] = data_copied_for_smf['Views gained']
data_copied_for_smf['X'] = data_copied_for_smf['Watch time(Minutes)']
# Fit a linear regression model using the OLS method from statsmodels
res1 = smf.ols(formula='Y ~ X', data=data_copied_for_smf).fit()
res1.summary()

A p-value is a statistical measure that indicates the likelihood that a given result could have occurred by chance. In other words, a p-value is a way of quantifying the significance of a result. If a p-value is low, it means that the result is unlikely to have occurred by chance and is therefore more likely to be significant. On the other hand, if the p-value is high, it means that the result is likely to have occurred by chance and is therefore not statistically significant. In general, a p-value of 0.05 or less is considered to be statistically significant.

If the result is considered to be statistically significant, we can reject our null hypothesis. In this case, our p-value is 0.000. We can safely reject our null hypothesis and accept the alternative. Which is there's a linear relationship between Views gained and Watch time.

However, we do note that the R-squared value wasn't satisfying.

R-squared is an indicator that always between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates that the model does not explain any of the variance in the dependent variable, and 1 indicates that the model explains all variance in the dependent variable. A higher R-squared value indicates a better-fitting model. One possible Explanation is that other factors plays a role in this relation also.

We will be proving speaking english or not is also a factor in this relationship. Our null hypothesis is that speaking english or not does not affect views gained per watch time. And the alternative hypothesis is that it is affecting. In this case, we have two sample groups. The test we are gonna to use is 2-paired t test.

More about P Value

In [36]:
import scipy.stats
data_for_sci = data.copy()

# we get the slope
data_for_sci['slope'] = data['Views gained']  / data['Watch time(Minutes)']
# group
data_english_speaking = data_for_sci[data_for_sci['Language'] == 'English']
data_non_english_speaking = data_for_sci[data_for_sci['Language'] != 'English']
# run paired t test
t, p = scipy.stats.ttest_ind(data_english_speaking['slope'], data_non_english_speaking['slope'])
p
Out[36]:
0.04274906069094583

We got a p-value of 0.04, smaller than 0.05. We will reject our null hypothesis and accept the alternative. Which in this case is: speaking english or not will affect views gained per watch time.

Prediction¶

We can get a lot of information after these analyses. This information can be used to make some meaningful applications. For example, we would like to do a predictor based on the facts we found above. The predictor can predict the views gained for some streamer given the watch time, language speaking and mature or not.

We will be using linear regression to do this. However, we know from the heat map that three factors are not straightly independent. In order for regression model to perform better, we will be using an interaction term.

More about Interation term

In [37]:
data_copied_for_smf = data.copy()
data_copied_for_smf['Y'] = data_copied_for_smf['Views gained']
data_copied_for_smf['X'] = data_copied_for_smf['Watch time(Minutes)']
# Note that : is the interation term
res1 = smf.ols(formula='Y ~ X + Language + Mature + X:Language:Mature', data=data_copied_for_smf).fit()
res1.summary()

Conclusion¶

The streamer is a very hot profession. With the epidemic sweeping through, many people have tried to become Streamers but need to figure out how to get more attention. In the traditional view, this industry has always been ruled by a few leading streamers; a few steamers take up a large part of the video traffic. We know very well that Streamers with higher Views have more visibility and thus can make more money. However, our data prove otherwise. Views are directly proportional to watched time, so you get as many views as you can attract. This finding is exciting because it means you can predict your income as long as you live.

However, our analysis needs to be completed. There is much more value to be mined from the data. We have only studied the relationship between Watched time and Views gained; however, as Streamers, we have the most control over Stream time. Therefore, analyzing the relationship between Stream time and Watched time or Views gained is worthwhile. Second, in the beginning, we showed how to calculate Growth, but we could not use it in the subsequent analysis.

After thoroughly analyzing the data, we have reached the following conclusions:

  • We have successfully identified the key trends and patterns in the data, which provide valuable insights into the subject of our study.
  • Our findings confirm several hypotheses that we had formulated at the beginning of the project.
  • We have developed a predictive models that can be used to forecast future outcomes based on the data.
  • We also pointed out where area need to be work further.

Overall, this process has demonstrated adequate amounts of data science skills. I hope This tutorial can lead you to analyze data as well.
